Note:
==============================================================================
BLAKE3 - Cryptographic hash, MAC, KDF, and XOF per the official BLAKE3 spec
==============================================================================

BLAKE3 is a tree-mode hash function built on top of a single compression
function derived from ChaCha. It produces 256-bit output by default and an
arbitrary length output in XOF mode. Designed by O'Connor, Aumasson, Neves,
Wilcox-O'Hearn (2020).

Construction:
  1. The input is split into 1024-byte chunks. Each chunk is processed in
     64-byte blocks by the compression function, with CHUNK_START set on
     the first block of a chunk and CHUNK_END set on the last block. Only
     the last block's output contributes the chunk's 32-byte chaining value.
  2. Chaining values are merged pairwise in a binary tree via the same
     compression function with PARENT set. The final compression at the
     root sets ROOT.
  3. The root may be expanded as an XOF by repeatedly calling the
     compression function on the final block with ROOT set and an
     incrementing block counter.

IV (identical to SHA-256 IV):
  0x6A09E667, 0xBB67AE85, 0x3C6EF372, 0xA54FF53A,
  0x510E527F, 0x9B05688C, 0x1F83D9AB, 0x5BE0CD19

Flags (LSB-first bit positions):
  CHUNK_START          = 0x01
  CHUNK_END            = 0x02
  PARENT               = 0x04
  ROOT                 = 0x08
  KEYED_HASH           = 0x10
  DERIVE_KEY_CONTEXT   = 0x20
  DERIVE_KEY_MATERIAL  = 0x40

Compression: 7 rounds of column + diagonal G permutations on a 16-word
state, exactly the ChaCha quarter-round structure with message-word
injection.

G(state, a, b, c, d, mx, my):
  v[a] = v[a] + v[b] + mx
  v[d] = rotr32(v[d] XOR v[a], 16)
  v[c] = v[c] + v[d]
  v[b] = rotr32(v[b] XOR v[c], 12)
  v[a] = v[a] + v[b] + my
  v[d] = rotr32(v[d] XOR v[a], 8)
  v[c] = v[c] + v[d]
  v[b] = rotr32(v[b] XOR v[c], 7)

Message permutation between rounds:
  MSG_PERMUTATION = [2, 6, 3, 10, 7, 0, 4, 13, 1, 11, 12, 5, 9, 14, 15, 8]

Side-channel posture:
- No secret-dependent branches. All loops are length-driven, not key-
  or input-content driven.
- No secret-dependent memory accesses. Indices are loop counters.
- Constant-time at the algorithm level.

Out of scope:
- Power analysis (requires hardware countermeasures).
- Fault injection (requires platform mitigations).

References:
- BLAKE3 spec: https://github.com/BLAKE3-team/BLAKE3-specs/blob/master/blake3.pdf
- Reference test vectors: https://github.com/BLAKE3-team/BLAKE3/blob/master/test_vectors/test_vectors.json
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "runtime/core/memory/arena.runa" as Arena

Constant BLAKE3_U32_MASK as Integer is 4294967295
Constant BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE as Integer is 64
Constant BLAKE3_CHUNK_SIZE as Integer is 1024
Constant BLAKE3_KEY_SIZE as Integer is 32
Constant BLAKE3_OUT_SIZE as Integer is 32
Constant BLAKE3_CV_SIZE as Integer is 32

Constant BLAKE3_FLAG_CHUNK_START as Integer is 1
Constant BLAKE3_FLAG_CHUNK_END as Integer is 2
Constant BLAKE3_FLAG_PARENT as Integer is 4
Constant BLAKE3_FLAG_ROOT as Integer is 8
Constant BLAKE3_FLAG_KEYED_HASH as Integer is 16
Constant BLAKE3_FLAG_DERIVE_KEY_CONTEXT as Integer is 32
Constant BLAKE3_FLAG_DERIVE_KEY_MATERIAL as Integer is 64

Note: ============================================================================
Note: 32-bit arithmetic helpers (constant-time integer ops)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "blake3_u32_add" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Modular 32-bit addition: (a + b) mod 2^32. Runa Integer is 64-bit signed,
    so we mask the sum to drop any bits beyond bit 31 to emulate the u32
    wraparound used throughout the BLAKE3 spec.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Plain add followed by bitwise_and with U32_MASK = 2^32 - 1. Both inputs
    must already be in [0, 2^32). Result is in [0, 2^32).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One add, one mask. Sub-nanosecond. A future codegen pass can detect the
    pattern and emit a single 32-bit add instruction.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time (pure arithmetic, no branches).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let sum_value be a plus b
    Return sum_value bitwise_and BLAKE3_U32_MASK
End Process

Process called "blake3_rotr32" takes value as Integer, n as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Right-rotate a 32-bit value by n positions. Used by the G permutation
    with rotations of 16, 12, 8, and 7 bits per BLAKE3 spec section 2.4.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Computes ((value >> n) | (value << (32-n))) mod 2^32. Since Runa
    Integer division and multiplication by powers of two are the standard
    shift primitives, we multiply for the left half and divide for the
    right half, then OR and mask to 32 bits.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One divide-by-power-of-2, one multiply-by-power-of-2, one OR, one mask.
    Sub-nanosecond. A future Runa codegen pass can lower this to a single
    ROR instruction once recognized.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: timing depends only on n (compile-time public constant
    in every call site below), never on value.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let v32 be value bitwise_and BLAKE3_U32_MASK
    Let n_mod be n modulo by 32
    If n_mod is equal to 0:
        Return v32
    End If

    Let shift_right be 1
    Let ir be 0
    While ir is less than n_mod:
        Set shift_right to shift_right multiplied by 2
        Set ir to ir plus 1
    End While
    Let shift_left be 1
    Let il be 0
    Let left_count be 32 minus n_mod
    While il is less than left_count:
        Set shift_left to shift_left multiplied by 2
        Set il to il plus 1
    End While

    Let right_part be v32 divided by shift_right
    Let left_part be v32 multiplied by shift_left
    Set left_part to left_part bitwise_and BLAKE3_U32_MASK
    Let combined be right_part bitwise_or left_part
    Return combined bitwise_and BLAKE3_U32_MASK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: BLAKE3 IV (same as SHA-256 IV per FIPS 180-4)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "blake3_iv_word" takes index as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns IV[index] for index in 0..7. The BLAKE3 IV is identical to the
    SHA-256 IV: the 32-bit fractional parts of the square roots of the
    first 8 primes (2, 3, 5, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Branch lookup. Stage1 has limited static-array support; a direct
    case-by-case return is equivalent in cost and is fully constant-time
    for the public index parameter.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    8-way branch resolved at compile time when callers pass literal indices
    (which is the case for every internal call site below).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: index is always a compile-time integer in callers.
    @End Security_Scope

    If index is equal to 0:
        Return 1779033703
    End If
    If index is equal to 1:
        Return 3144134277
    End If
    If index is equal to 2:
        Return 1013904242
    End If
    If index is equal to 3:
        Return 2773480762
    End If
    If index is equal to 4:
        Return 1359893119
    End If
    If index is equal to 5:
        Return 2600822924
    End If
    If index is equal to 6:
        Return 528734635
    End If
    If index is equal to 7:
        Return 1541459225
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: BLAKE3 message-word permutation
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "blake3_msg_perm_index" takes i as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    BLAKE3 spec MSG_PERMUTATION = [2, 6, 3, 10, 7, 0, 4, 13, 1, 11, 12, 5,
    9, 14, 15, 8]. After each compression round (except the last), the
    message words are permuted: m'[i] = m[MSG_PERMUTATION[i]].
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Direct lookup by branch. Public index from a loop counter; constant-time
    by construction.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    16-way branch resolved inline at each call site by the compiler's
    constant-folding pass when the caller passes a literal.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: index is a public loop counter.
    @End Security_Scope

    If i is equal to 0:
        Return 2
    End If
    If i is equal to 1:
        Return 6
    End If
    If i is equal to 2:
        Return 3
    End If
    If i is equal to 3:
        Return 10
    End If
    If i is equal to 4:
        Return 7
    End If
    If i is equal to 5:
        Return 0
    End If
    If i is equal to 6:
        Return 4
    End If
    If i is equal to 7:
        Return 13
    End If
    If i is equal to 8:
        Return 1
    End If
    If i is equal to 9:
        Return 11
    End If
    If i is equal to 10:
        Return 12
    End If
    If i is equal to 11:
        Return 5
    End If
    If i is equal to 12:
        Return 9
    End If
    If i is equal to 13:
        Return 14
    End If
    If i is equal to 14:
        Return 15
    End If
    If i is equal to 15:
        Return 8
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: G permutation
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "blake3_g" takes v_state as Integer, a as Integer, b as Integer, c as Integer, d as Integer, mx as Integer, my as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    BLAKE3 G function per spec section 2.4. Mixes four state words v[a],
    v[b], v[c], v[d] with two message words mx and my. v_state stores the
    16 32-bit state words as 8-byte qwords at offsets index*8.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
      v[a] = v[a] + v[b] + mx
      v[d] = rotr32(v[d] XOR v[a], 16)
      v[c] = v[c] + v[d]
      v[b] = rotr32(v[b] XOR v[c], 12)
      v[a] = v[a] + v[b] + my
      v[d] = rotr32(v[d] XOR v[a], 8)
      v[c] = v[c] + v[d]
      v[b] = rotr32(v[b] XOR v[c], 7)
    All additions are mod 2^32 via blake3_u32_add. Inputs mx and my are
    already in [0, 2^32) from the message-word loader.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Twelve 32-bit adds, four rotations, four XORs. Eight G calls per
    round, seven rounds per compression: 56 G calls per block. The hot
    loop. A future SIMD-vectorized lowering can pack four lanes of the
    state into a 128-bit register and run all four column or diagonal Gs
    in parallel.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: no secret-dependent branches or memory accesses; all
    indices are caller-supplied compile-time constants from the
    compression round structure.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let off_a be a multiplied by 8
    Let off_b be b multiplied by 8
    Let off_c be c multiplied by 8
    Let off_d be d multiplied by 8

    Let va be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with v_state, off_a
    Let vb be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with v_state, off_b
    Let vc be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with v_state, off_c
    Let vd be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with v_state, off_d

    Let va_ab be proc blake3_u32_add with va, vb
    Set va to proc blake3_u32_add with va_ab, mx

    Let vd_xa be vd bitwise_xor va
    Set vd to proc blake3_rotr32 with vd_xa, 16

    Set vc to proc blake3_u32_add with vc, vd

    Let vb_xc be vb bitwise_xor vc
    Set vb to proc blake3_rotr32 with vb_xc, 12

    Let va_ab2 be proc blake3_u32_add with va, vb
    Set va to proc blake3_u32_add with va_ab2, my

    Let vd_xa2 be vd bitwise_xor va
    Set vd to proc blake3_rotr32 with vd_xa2, 8

    Set vc to proc blake3_u32_add with vc, vd

    Let vb_xc2 be vb bitwise_xor vc
    Set vb to proc blake3_rotr32 with vb_xc2, 7

    proc memory_set_qword from Memory with v_state, off_a, va
    proc memory_set_qword from Memory with v_state, off_b, vb
    proc memory_set_qword from Memory with v_state, off_c, vc
    proc memory_set_qword from Memory with v_state, off_d, vd
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: One compression round (column step + diagonal step) with message m
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "blake3_round" takes v_state as Integer, m_state as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Performs one BLAKE3 compression round on v_state using the 16 message
    words in m_state. Per spec section 2.4, a round consists of:
      column step:   G(0,4,8,12,m0,m1), G(1,5,9,13,m2,m3),
                     G(2,6,10,14,m4,m5), G(3,7,11,15,m6,m7)
      diagonal step: G(0,5,10,15,m8,m9), G(1,6,11,12,m10,m11),
                     G(2,7,8,13,m12,m13), G(3,4,9,14,m14,m15)
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Reads each message word from m_state (stored as qwords at offsets
    index*8) and invokes blake3_g eight times in the order above.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Eight G calls. Sixteen message-word reads. Trivially parallelizable
    across the four column Gs (independent) and the four diagonal Gs
    (also independent within their step).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time. All indices are loop-iteration-independent compile-time
    constants.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let m0 be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with m_state, 0
    Let m1 be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with m_state, 8
    Let m2 be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with m_state, 16
    Let m3 be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with m_state, 24
    Let m4 be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with m_state, 32
    Let m5 be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with m_state, 40
    Let m6 be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with m_state, 48
    Let m7 be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with m_state, 56
    Let m8 be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with m_state, 64
    Let m9 be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with m_state, 72
    Let m10 be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with m_state, 80
    Let m11 be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with m_state, 88
    Let m12 be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with m_state, 96
    Let m13 be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with m_state, 104
    Let m14 be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with m_state, 112
    Let m15 be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with m_state, 120

    proc blake3_g with v_state, 0, 4, 8, 12, m0, m1
    proc blake3_g with v_state, 1, 5, 9, 13, m2, m3
    proc blake3_g with v_state, 2, 6, 10, 14, m4, m5
    proc blake3_g with v_state, 3, 7, 11, 15, m6, m7

    proc blake3_g with v_state, 0, 5, 10, 15, m8, m9
    proc blake3_g with v_state, 1, 6, 11, 12, m10, m11
    proc blake3_g with v_state, 2, 7, 8, 13, m12, m13
    proc blake3_g with v_state, 3, 4, 9, 14, m14, m15
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Permute the message words: m'[i] = m[MSG_PERMUTATION[i]]
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "blake3_permute_message" takes arena as Integer, m_state as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Applies MSG_PERMUTATION in place. Spec section 2.4 calls for this
    after each round except the last (rounds 1..6 of the 7-round
    sequence; we apply it between rounds, so 6 invocations total).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocates a 16-word scratch buffer in the arena, copies the
    permuted words into it, then writes them back into m_state. This avoids
    the write-into-while-reading data dependency of a strict-in-place
    permutation, which is required for correctness because some source
    indices alias destinations earlier in the permutation table.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Sixteen reads, sixteen writes, with one arena allocation per call.
    Cost is small relative to the compression rounds themselves.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: permutation indices come from a public table.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let tmp be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, 128
    If tmp is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 16:
        Let src_idx be proc blake3_msg_perm_index with i
        Let src_off be src_idx multiplied by 8
        Let src_val be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with m_state, src_off
        Let dst_off be i multiplied by 8
        proc memory_set_qword from Memory with tmp, dst_off, src_val
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let j be 0
    While j is less than 16:
        Let off_j be j multiplied by 8
        Let val_j be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with tmp, off_j
        proc memory_set_qword from Memory with m_state, off_j, val_j
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: BLAKE3 compression function
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "blake3_load_block_words" takes block as Integer, m_state as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Loads the 64-byte block as 16 little-endian 32-bit words into m_state
    (one qword per word at offset i*8). Used by both chunk and parent
    compressions; the parent compression treats the two child CVs as a
    64-byte block.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    For i in 0..15: load 4 little-endian bytes from block[i*4 .. i*4+3]
    into a u32 and store it at m_state[i*8].
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Sixteen 4-byte loads. On a little-endian CPU the codegen-level
    instruction selection lowers each 4-byte little-endian load to an
    aligned 32-bit movl when the alignment can be proven.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: byte indices are loop-counter driven.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 16:
        Let base be i multiplied by 4
        Let b0 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with block, base
        Let b1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with block, base plus 1
        Let b2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with block, base plus 2
        Let b3 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with block, base plus 3
        Let w be b0 plus b1 multiplied by 256
        Set w to w plus b2 multiplied by 65536
        Set w to w plus b3 multiplied by 16777216
        Let off be i multiplied by 8
        proc memory_set_qword from Memory with m_state, off, w
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "blake3_compress" takes arena as Integer, cv as Integer, block as Integer, counter as Integer, block_len as Integer, flags as Integer, out_state as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes the BLAKE3 compression function per spec section 2.4 and
    writes the full 16-word output state into out_state (as qwords at
    8-byte stride). Callers that only need the 8-word chaining value use
    the first 32 bytes; XOF callers use all 64 bytes.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Build initial 16-word state v:
         v[0..7]  = cv[0..7]
         v[8..11] = IV[0..3]
         v[12]    = counter & 0xFFFFFFFF
         v[13]    = (counter >> 32) & 0xFFFFFFFF
         v[14]    = block_len
         v[15]    = flags
    2. Load the 64-byte block as 16 little-endian u32 into m_state.
    3. For round in 0..6:
         a. blake3_round(v, m_state)
         b. If round < 6: blake3_permute_message(m_state)
    4. Finalize:
         out[0..7]  = v[0..7] XOR v[8..15]
         out[8..15] = cv[0..7] XOR v[8..15]
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Seven rounds + six permutations per compression. 56 G calls. Per the
    BLAKE3 paper, ~3-6 cycles per byte on a scalar single core, well
    below 1 cycle per byte with AVX2 SIMD. A future Runa SIMD lowering
    is the path to that.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time at the algorithmic level: no secret-dependent branches
    or memory accesses anywhere in the round loop. The compression input
    block_len, counter, and flags are all caller-supplied public state
    machine outputs (chunk index, position in chunk, mode). The chaining
    value cv is the only secret-derived input and it is treated only as
    arithmetic operand throughout.

    Out of scope:
    - Power analysis (requires hardware countermeasures).
    - Fault injection (requires platform mitigations).
    @End Security_Scope

    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If cv is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If out_state is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let v_state be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, 128
    If v_state is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let m_state be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, 128
    If m_state is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: v[0..7] = cv[0..7]
    Let ci be 0
    While ci is less than 8:
        Let cv_off be ci multiplied by 4
        Let cb0 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with cv, cv_off
        Let cb1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with cv, cv_off plus 1
        Let cb2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with cv, cv_off plus 2
        Let cb3 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with cv, cv_off plus 3
        Let cw be cb0 plus cb1 multiplied by 256
        Set cw to cw plus cb2 multiplied by 65536
        Set cw to cw plus cb3 multiplied by 16777216
        Let v_off be ci multiplied by 8
        proc memory_set_qword from Memory with v_state, v_off, cw
        Set ci to ci plus 1
    End While

    Note: v[8..11] = IV[0..3]
    Let ivi be 0
    While ivi is less than 4:
        Let iv_word be proc blake3_iv_word with ivi
        Let iv_slot be ivi plus 8
        Let v_off2 be iv_slot multiplied by 8
        proc memory_set_qword from Memory with v_state, v_off2, iv_word
        Set ivi to ivi plus 1
    End While

    Note: Counter low/high
    Let counter_low be counter bitwise_and BLAKE3_U32_MASK
    Let counter_high_div be 1
    Let chi be 0
    While chi is less than 32:
        Set counter_high_div to counter_high_div multiplied by 2
        Set chi to chi plus 1
    End While
    Let counter_high be counter divided by counter_high_div
    Set counter_high to counter_high bitwise_and BLAKE3_U32_MASK

    proc memory_set_qword from Memory with v_state, 96, counter_low
    proc memory_set_qword from Memory with v_state, 104, counter_high
    proc memory_set_qword from Memory with v_state, 112, block_len
    proc memory_set_qword from Memory with v_state, 120, flags

    Note: Load message block
    proc blake3_load_block_words with block, m_state

    Note: 7 rounds with permutation between them
    Let r be 0
    While r is less than 7:
        proc blake3_round with v_state, m_state
        If r is less than 6:
            proc blake3_permute_message with arena, m_state
        End If
        Set r to r plus 1
    End While

    Note: Finalize: out[0..7] = v[0..7] XOR v[8..15], out[8..15] = cv_words[0..7] XOR v[8..15]
    Note: We need cv as words again to XOR with v[8..15]. Read fresh from cv.
    Let fi be 0
    While fi is less than 8:
        Let v_lo_off be fi multiplied by 8
        Let fi_hi_slot be fi plus 8
        Let v_hi_off be fi_hi_slot multiplied by 8
        Let v_lo be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with v_state, v_lo_off
        Let v_hi be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with v_state, v_hi_off
        Let out_lo be v_lo bitwise_xor v_hi
        Let out_lo_off be fi multiplied by 8
        proc memory_set_qword from Memory with out_state, out_lo_off, out_lo

        Let cv_off2 be fi multiplied by 4
        Let cvb0 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with cv, cv_off2
        Let cvb1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with cv, cv_off2 plus 1
        Let cvb2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with cv, cv_off2 plus 2
        Let cvb3 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with cv, cv_off2 plus 3
        Let cv_word be cvb0 plus cvb1 multiplied by 256
        Set cv_word to cv_word plus cvb2 multiplied by 65536
        Set cv_word to cv_word plus cvb3 multiplied by 16777216
        Let out_hi be cv_word bitwise_xor v_hi
        Let out_hi_off be fi_hi_slot multiplied by 8
        proc memory_set_qword from Memory with out_state, out_hi_off, out_hi
        Set fi to fi plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Serialize first 8 state words (chaining value) into a 32-byte buffer
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "blake3_state_to_cv" takes state as Integer, cv_out as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Converts the first 8 words of a compression-function output state into
    the 32-byte chaining value layout (little-endian, used as input to the
    next compression).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    For i in 0..7: read state word as qword from offset i*8, write four
    little-endian bytes at cv_out[i*4 .. i*4+3].
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Eight word stores. Trivial.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: loop-counter indexing only.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 8:
        Let off_i be i multiplied by 8
        Let w be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with state, off_i
        Let base be i multiplied by 4
        Let b0 be w bitwise_and 255
        Let b1 be w divided by 256
        Set b1 to b1 bitwise_and 255
        Let b2 be w divided by 65536
        Set b2 to b2 bitwise_and 255
        Let b3 be w divided by 16777216
        Set b3 to b3 bitwise_and 255
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with cv_out, base, b0
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with cv_out, base plus 1, b1
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with cv_out, base plus 2, b2
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with cv_out, base plus 3, b3
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Serialize full 16-word state into a 64-byte buffer (for XOF output)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "blake3_state_to_bytes" takes state as Integer, out as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Serializes all 16 state words into 64 little-endian bytes. Used to
    materialize a single XOF output block.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    For i in 0..15: read word from state[i*8], write little-endian bytes
    at out[i*4 .. i*4+3].
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Sixteen word stores.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: loop-counter indexing only.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 16:
        Let off_i be i multiplied by 8
        Let w be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with state, off_i
        Let base be i multiplied by 4
        Let b0 be w bitwise_and 255
        Let b1 be w divided by 256
        Set b1 to b1 bitwise_and 255
        Let b2 be w divided by 65536
        Set b2 to b2 bitwise_and 255
        Let b3 be w divided by 16777216
        Set b3 to b3 bitwise_and 255
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with out, base, b0
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with out, base plus 1, b1
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with out, base plus 2, b2
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with out, base plus 3, b3
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Process one chunk (up to 1024 bytes) and emit its 32-byte chaining value
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "blake3_compress_chunk" takes arena as Integer, key_cv as Integer, input as Integer, input_off as Integer, chunk_len as Integer, chunk_counter as Integer, base_flags as Integer, cv_out as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Processes one chunk's worth of input bytes (1..1024). Splits into
    64-byte blocks; the first block has CHUNK_START set; the last has
    CHUNK_END set. Only the last compression's chaining value contributes
    to cv_out.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Set chaining value = key_cv (initial chunk CV is the key per spec).
    2. For each 64-byte block in the chunk:
         a. Build flags = base_flags | (CHUNK_START if first block) |
            (CHUNK_END if last block).
         b. Build block buffer: copy block bytes; zero-pad if last block
            has fewer than 64 bytes.
         c. Compute compression output.
         d. If not last block: update chaining value from first 8 words.
         e. If last block: serialize first 8 words into cv_out.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    ceil(chunk_len / 64) compressions per chunk. For a full chunk that
    is 16 compressions. Block buffer is reused; only one arena allocation
    per chunk.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time per block. The number of blocks processed depends only
    on chunk_len (the chunk boundary is a public state-machine value).
    @End Security_Scope

    If chunk_len is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If chunk_len is greater than BLAKE3_CHUNK_SIZE:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let block_buf be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE
    If block_buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let cv_buf be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_CV_SIZE
    If cv_buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let state_buf be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, 128
    If state_buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize CV from key_cv
    Let ki be 0
    While ki is less than BLAKE3_CV_SIZE:
        Let kb be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with key_cv, ki
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with cv_buf, ki, kb
        Set ki to ki plus 1
    End While

    Let pos be 0
    Let is_first_block be 1
    Let blocks_done be 0

    Note: Handle empty chunk case: still need one compression with CHUNK_START | CHUNK_END
    If chunk_len is equal to 0:
        Note: Zero block_buf
        Let zi be 0
        While zi is less than BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE:
            proc memory_set_byte from Memory with block_buf, zi, 0
            Set zi to zi plus 1
        End While
        Let empty_flags be base_flags bitwise_or BLAKE3_FLAG_CHUNK_START
        Set empty_flags to empty_flags bitwise_or BLAKE3_FLAG_CHUNK_END
        proc blake3_compress with arena, cv_buf, block_buf, chunk_counter, 0, empty_flags, state_buf
        proc blake3_state_to_cv with state_buf, cv_out
        Return 1
    End If

    While pos is less than chunk_len:
        Let remaining be chunk_len minus pos
        Let this_len be remaining
        If this_len is greater than BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE:
            Set this_len to BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE
        End If
        Let is_last_block be 0
        If pos plus this_len is equal to chunk_len:
            Set is_last_block to 1
        End If

        Note: Build block_buf
        Let bi be 0
        While bi is less than this_len:
            Let sb be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with input, input_off plus pos plus bi
            proc memory_set_byte from Memory with block_buf, bi, sb
            Set bi to bi plus 1
        End While
        Note: Zero-pad remainder of block to 64 bytes
        Let pi be this_len
        While pi is less than BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE:
            proc memory_set_byte from Memory with block_buf, pi, 0
            Set pi to pi plus 1
        End While

        Let block_flags be base_flags
        If is_first_block is equal to 1:
            Set block_flags to block_flags bitwise_or BLAKE3_FLAG_CHUNK_START
        End If
        If is_last_block is equal to 1:
            Set block_flags to block_flags bitwise_or BLAKE3_FLAG_CHUNK_END
        End If

        proc blake3_compress with arena, cv_buf, block_buf, chunk_counter, this_len, block_flags, state_buf

        If is_last_block is equal to 1:
            proc blake3_state_to_cv with state_buf, cv_out
        Otherwise:
            proc blake3_state_to_cv with state_buf, cv_buf
        End If

        Set pos to pos plus this_len
        Set is_first_block to 0
        Set blocks_done to blocks_done plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Compute the parent compression of two child CVs
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "blake3_parent_cv" takes arena as Integer, key_cv as Integer, left_cv as Integer, right_cv as Integer, base_flags as Integer, out_state as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Combines two 32-byte child chaining values into a parent state. The
    64-byte block is left_cv concatenated with right_cv. Counter is 0,
    block_len is 64, flags include PARENT.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Build a 64-byte parent_block by concatenating left_cv and right_cv.
    2. Compress with cv = key_cv, counter = 0, block_len = 64,
       flags = base_flags | PARENT.
    3. Write the full 16-word output state to out_state.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One compression call. Reusable from both the standard tree-merge
    and from the root-output emission.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let parent_block be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE
    If parent_block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 32:
        Let lb be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with left_cv, i
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with parent_block, i, lb
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than 32:
        Let rb be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with right_cv, j
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with parent_block, j plus 32, rb
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Let parent_flags be base_flags bitwise_or BLAKE3_FLAG_PARENT
    proc blake3_compress with arena, key_cv, parent_block, 0, BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE, parent_flags, out_state
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Build the key_cv buffer from either the default IV (8 little-endian
Note: words of IV) or from a caller-provided 32-byte key (already 8 LE words).
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "blake3_default_iv_to_cv" takes cv_out as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Serialize the eight IV words as little-endian into the 32-byte CV
    buffer for the default-hash and DERIVE_KEY_CONTEXT modes.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    For i in 0..7: write IV[i] little-endian into cv_out[i*4..i*4+3].
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Trivial; eight 4-byte stores.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time. IV is public.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 8:
        Let w be proc blake3_iv_word with i
        Let base be i multiplied by 4
        Let b0 be w bitwise_and 255
        Let b1 be w divided by 256
        Set b1 to b1 bitwise_and 255
        Let b2 be w divided by 65536
        Set b2 to b2 bitwise_and 255
        Let b3 be w divided by 16777216
        Set b3 to b3 bitwise_and 255
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with cv_out, base, b0
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with cv_out, base plus 1, b1
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with cv_out, base plus 2, b2
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with cv_out, base plus 3, b3
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Subtree-rooted tree merge using a stack of pending CVs
Note: ============================================================================
Note:
Pending-CV stack design (per BLAKE3 spec section 5.1.2):
  - As each chunk emits a CV, push it.
  - Before pushing a new CV, check the chunk counter just completed.
    If the count of trailing zero bits in (chunk_counter + 1) is t,
    merge t pairs from the top of the stack before pushing.
  - At the end, merge what remains right-to-left to form the root.

This implements the "complete subtrees" rule: a subtree of 2^k chunks
is finalized as soon as its rightmost chunk is processed.
:End Note

Process called "blake3_count_trailing_zeros" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Counts trailing zero bits in a 64-bit unsigned value. Used to decide
    how many pending CVs to merge when a chunk completes (per BLAKE3
    spec, subtree merges happen when the chunk counter rolls a complete
    power-of-two boundary).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Iterates from bit 0 upward, dividing by 2 each step, stopping at the
    first set bit. For value == 0 returns 64.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Worst-case 64 iterations. Caller hot-path passes the incremented
    chunk counter, which on every practical workload has only a handful
    of trailing zeros. The codegen-level instruction selection lowers
    this loop to BSF/TZCNT on architectures that expose those primitives.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The iteration count depends on the value, which is a public chunk
    index (derived from the position in the input stream, not from any
    secret). No timing channel exposes secret material here.
    @End Security_Scope

    If value is equal to 0:
        Return 64
    End If
    Let n be 0
    Let v be value
    While v bitwise_and 1 is equal to 0:
        Set v to v divided by 2
        Set n to n plus 1
        If n is greater than 63:
            Return n
        End If
    End While
    Return n
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Hasher state (in arena)
Note: ============================================================================
Note:
Layout: contiguous arena block holding:
  - cv_stack: 54 slots * 32 bytes = 1728 bytes (max stack depth for
               2^54 chunks; the spec allows up to 2^54 chunks).
  - stack_size: 1 qword (Integer)
  - chunk_counter: 1 qword (Integer)
  - key_cv: 32 bytes (the keying material - IV for default, key for
              keyed_hash, intermediate hash for derive_key)
  - base_flags: 1 qword (KEYED_HASH or DERIVE_KEY_MATERIAL, or 0)
  - chunk_buf: 1024 bytes (accumulating bytes for the current chunk)
  - chunk_buf_len: 1 qword (current fill of chunk_buf)

All fields are accessed via memory_get_qword / memory_set_qword and
memory_get_byte / memory_set_byte through documented offsets.

For our streaming API we accept the full input as a single contiguous
buffer (hash, keyed_hash, derive_key). The streaming-style Hasher
object is a logical structure internal to hash(), reset per call.
:End Note

Constant BLAKE3_STACK_MAX_DEPTH as Integer is 54
Constant BLAKE3_HASHER_STACK_OFF as Integer is 0
Constant BLAKE3_HASHER_STACK_SIZE_OFF as Integer is 1728
Constant BLAKE3_HASHER_CHUNK_COUNTER_OFF as Integer is 1736
Constant BLAKE3_HASHER_KEY_CV_OFF as Integer is 1744
Constant BLAKE3_HASHER_BASE_FLAGS_OFF as Integer is 1776
Constant BLAKE3_HASHER_CHUNK_BUF_OFF as Integer is 1784
Constant BLAKE3_HASHER_TOTAL_SIZE as Integer is 2808

Process called "blake3_hasher_init" takes arena as Integer, key_cv as Integer, base_flags as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocates and initializes a hasher state in the arena. key_cv is the
    32-byte initial chaining value used at every chunk root: for default
    hash this is the IV, for keyed_hash it is the user key, for
    DERIVE_KEY_MATERIAL pass it is the intermediate key derived from the
    DERIVE_KEY_CONTEXT pass.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocates BLAKE3_HASHER_TOTAL_SIZE bytes; copies key_cv into the
    key_cv slot; zeros the stack-size and chunk-counter slots; sets
    base_flags.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One arena allocation, a small zeroing loop, a 32-byte copy.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let h be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_HASHER_TOTAL_SIZE
    If h is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_qword from Memory with h, BLAKE3_HASHER_STACK_SIZE_OFF, 0
    proc memory_set_qword from Memory with h, BLAKE3_HASHER_CHUNK_COUNTER_OFF, 0
    proc memory_set_qword from Memory with h, BLAKE3_HASHER_BASE_FLAGS_OFF, base_flags

    Let ki be 0
    While ki is less than 32:
        Let kb be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with key_cv, ki
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with h, BLAKE3_HASHER_KEY_CV_OFF plus ki, kb
        Set ki to ki plus 1
    End While

    Return h
End Process

Process called "blake3_push_cv" takes h as Integer, new_cv as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Pushes a 32-byte CV onto the hasher's pending-CV stack. Before pushing,
    merges any complete subtrees: if the chunk just emitted has counter c,
    the number of trailing zero bits in (c+1) is the number of subtree
    merges to perform.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Reads stack_size and the chunk_counter (which has already been
    incremented past the chunk that produced this CV). For each trailing
    zero bit in chunk_counter, pop the top of the stack as left_cv and
    treat new_cv as right_cv, compute parent CV via blake3_parent_cv,
    serialize first 8 words back into new_cv. After the merges, push
    new_cv onto the stack.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Worst case one parent compression per push (amortized O(1)). The
    cv_stack is a flat memory region inside the hasher.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time per merge.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let arena_ptr be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with h, BLAKE3_HASHER_KEY_CV_OFF
    Note: We don't store the arena pointer in the hasher; the caller must
    Note: pass the arena via a wrapper that supplies it. We'll route through
    Note: blake3_hasher_update_with_arena below which takes arena as a
    Note: parameter explicitly. The push helper takes arena directly.
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "blake3_push_cv_with_arena" takes arena as Integer, h as Integer, new_cv as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Same as blake3_push_cv but receives arena explicitly. This is the
    invocation path used by the streaming update procedure.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Per BLAKE3 spec section 5.1.2, before pushing the freshly-computed
    chunk CV, decide how many subtree merges to do based on trailing
    zeros of the just-completed chunk_counter (= total_chunks). Each
    merge pops the stack top as left_cv, uses our new_cv as right_cv,
    runs blake3_parent_cv to a state, copies first 8 words back to
    new_cv. After all merges, push new_cv.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Total work across the whole hash is O(n / 1024) for chunks plus
    O(n / 1024) for merges (the binary tree). Arena allocations per
    merge are reused via the compressor scratch.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time per merge.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let total_chunks be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with h, BLAKE3_HASHER_CHUNK_COUNTER_OFF
    Note: At call time, chunk_counter has been incremented to reflect the
    Note: chunk that just produced new_cv. Per spec, the number of merges
    Note: equals the count of trailing zero bits of total_chunks.
    Let merges be proc blake3_count_trailing_zeros with total_chunks

    Let key_cv_ptr be h plus BLAKE3_HASHER_KEY_CV_OFF
    Let base_flags be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with h, BLAKE3_HASHER_BASE_FLAGS_OFF

    Let parent_state be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, 128
    If parent_state is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than merges:
        Let stack_size be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with h, BLAKE3_HASHER_STACK_SIZE_OFF
        If stack_size is less than 1:
            Note: spec invariant violation; abort safely.
            Return 0
        End If
        Let stack_top_idx be stack_size minus 1
        Let left_off be stack_top_idx multiplied by 32
        Let left_ptr be h plus BLAKE3_HASHER_STACK_OFF plus left_off
        proc blake3_parent_cv with arena, key_cv_ptr, left_ptr, new_cv, base_flags, parent_state
        proc blake3_state_to_cv with parent_state, new_cv
        proc memory_set_qword from Memory with h, BLAKE3_HASHER_STACK_SIZE_OFF, stack_size minus 1
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Push new_cv
    Let stack_size_now be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with h, BLAKE3_HASHER_STACK_SIZE_OFF
    If stack_size_now is greater than 53:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let push_off be stack_size_now multiplied by 32
    Let push_ptr be h plus BLAKE3_HASHER_STACK_OFF plus push_off
    Let ci be 0
    While ci is less than 32:
        Let cvb be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with new_cv, ci
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with push_ptr, ci, cvb
        Set ci to ci plus 1
    End While
    proc memory_set_qword from Memory with h, BLAKE3_HASHER_STACK_SIZE_OFF, stack_size_now plus 1
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Compress the entire input into the hasher in 1024-byte chunks, except
Note: for the final chunk which is held back so we can apply ROOT correctly.
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "blake3_hash_input_to_root_state" takes arena as Integer, key_cv as Integer, base_flags as Integer, input as Integer, length as Integer, root_state_out as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Drives the BLAKE3 tree from start to finish, producing the final
    16-word root state. The strategy follows the reference implementation:

    - Special-case length 0: hash an empty chunk (only chunk with
      CHUNK_START | CHUNK_END | ROOT applied to a zero-length block).

    - Special-case length <= 1024: one chunk only; apply ROOT to that
      chunk's last block.

    - General case: process all chunks except the final one with normal
      flags, pushing each into the CV stack with subtree-merge logic.
      Then for the final chunk, the strategy is: after processing all
      complete subtrees, the final chunk's last-block compression
      carries ROOT if and only if the final chunk is alone (no pending
      CVs on the stack to merge). Otherwise the final chunk's CV is
      merged pairwise up the stack, and the topmost parent compression
      carries ROOT.

    The final-output rule (spec 5.1.2): the root output is the result of
    compressing the *leftmost* and *rightmost* subtrees at the final
    merge step, with ROOT set in the flags. For a single-chunk input the
    root flag is set on the chunk's last block.

    Implementation strategy:
    1. If length == 0: emit one chunk compression with empty block and
       flags = base_flags | CHUNK_START | CHUNK_END | ROOT directly into
       root_state_out.
    2. If length is at most 1024: emit chunk processing where the final
       block of the chunk has ROOT set, writing root_state_out directly.
    3. Otherwise: process chunks 0..n-2 normally (compress chunk, push
       CV with subtree merges). For chunk n-1 (the final chunk):
         - Process all-but-last block of the chunk normally.
         - Compress the chunk's last block normally (no ROOT) to obtain
           the chunk's CV.
         - Push that CV into the stack, but without ROOT (subtree merges
           still happen for non-ROOT level joins).
         - Now reduce the remaining stack to a single CV by repeatedly
           popping the top two and combining via PARENT, with ROOT set
           on the *last* combination only.
         - The final combination's state goes into root_state_out.

    However, the chunk's last-block-with-ROOT and parent-with-ROOT cases
    must be handled with care. The reference implementation uses an
    "output" structure that defers the ROOT-flagged compression until
    the consumer asks for output, allowing both single-chunk and
    multi-chunk inputs to share the same finalize path.

    We follow that approach:
       finalize() constructs an "output" representing either
       (a) chunk-style: cv=key_cv, block=last_block, counter=chunk_idx,
           block_len=last_len, flags=base_flags|CHUNK_START_maybe|CHUNK_END
           (no ROOT yet);
       or
       (b) parent-style: cv=key_cv, block=left_cv||right_cv, counter=0,
           block_len=64, flags=base_flags|PARENT (no ROOT yet).
       Then root output is the same compression with ROOT added.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Process the input in 1024-byte chunks, keeping the chunk_counter and
    stack in the hasher. For the last chunk we defer its CHUNK_END
    compression so that the "output" can be either (single-chunk) the
    chunk's last block with ROOT, or (multi-chunk) parent compressions
    merging the stack with ROOT on the final parent.

    Detailed flow:
      a. While remaining > 1024:
           process full 1024-byte chunk: blake3_compress_chunk with no
           ROOT, push CV via blake3_push_cv_with_arena (which performs
           subtree merges), advance input, increment chunk_counter
           appropriately. blake3_compress_chunk itself does not increment
           the hasher counter; we do it here.
      b. Now we have 1..1024 bytes left (the final chunk).
         If stack is empty (single chunk total): the chunk's last block
           must carry ROOT. We process chunk's blocks one at a time;
           on the last block we set CHUNK_END | ROOT and compress
           directly to root_state_out.
         Otherwise: process the final chunk normally (no ROOT) producing
           a CV. Then merge that CV up the stack right-to-left:
             - For each merge except the last: combine via blake3_parent_cv,
               serialize state to a CV, that becomes the new right CV.
             - For the *final* merge (when stack_size==1): combine via
               blake3_compress with PARENT|ROOT, writing into
               root_state_out directly.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(length) compression cost plus O(length / 1024) parent merges (very
    small relative to the chunk work).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time per block. The dispatch on number-of-chunks is on a
    public length value.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let h be proc blake3_hasher_init with arena, key_cv, base_flags
    If h is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Special case length == 0
    If length is equal to 0:
        Let zero_block be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE
        If zero_block is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let zi be 0
        While zi is less than BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE:
            proc memory_set_byte from Memory with zero_block, zi, 0
            Set zi to zi plus 1
        End While
        Let zflags be base_flags bitwise_or BLAKE3_FLAG_CHUNK_START
        Set zflags to zflags bitwise_or BLAKE3_FLAG_CHUNK_END
        Set zflags to zflags bitwise_or BLAKE3_FLAG_ROOT
        proc blake3_compress with arena, key_cv, zero_block, 0, 0, zflags, root_state_out
        Return 1
    End If

    Let input_off be 0
    Let remaining be length
    Let chunk_cv be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_CV_SIZE
    If chunk_cv is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Process all chunks except possibly the final one
    While remaining is greater than BLAKE3_CHUNK_SIZE:
        Let chunk_idx be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with h, BLAKE3_HASHER_CHUNK_COUNTER_OFF
        proc blake3_compress_chunk with arena, key_cv, input, input_off, BLAKE3_CHUNK_SIZE, chunk_idx, base_flags, chunk_cv
        Let new_counter be chunk_idx plus 1
        proc memory_set_qword from Memory with h, BLAKE3_HASHER_CHUNK_COUNTER_OFF, new_counter
        proc blake3_push_cv_with_arena with arena, h, chunk_cv
        Set input_off to input_off plus BLAKE3_CHUNK_SIZE
        Set remaining to remaining minus BLAKE3_CHUNK_SIZE
    End While

    Note: Now remaining is in [1, 1024]; this is the final chunk.
    Let stack_size_before_final be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with h, BLAKE3_HASHER_STACK_SIZE_OFF
    Let final_chunk_idx be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with h, BLAKE3_HASHER_CHUNK_COUNTER_OFF

    If stack_size_before_final is equal to 0:
        Note: Single chunk total. Process all-but-last block normally,
        Note: then the last block with ROOT into root_state_out.
        Let cv_buf be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_CV_SIZE
        If cv_buf is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let block_buf be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE
        If block_buf is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let state_scratch be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, 128
        If state_scratch is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Init cv = key_cv
        Let ki2 be 0
        While ki2 is less than BLAKE3_CV_SIZE:
            Let kb2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with key_cv, ki2
            proc memory_set_byte from Memory with cv_buf, ki2, kb2
            Set ki2 to ki2 plus 1
        End While

        Let pos be 0
        Let is_first_block be 1
        While pos is less than remaining:
            Let rem_in_chunk be remaining minus pos
            Let this_len be rem_in_chunk
            If this_len is greater than BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE:
                Set this_len to BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE
            End If
            Let is_last_block be 0
            If pos plus this_len is equal to remaining:
                Set is_last_block to 1
            End If

            Let bi be 0
            While bi is less than this_len:
                Let sb be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with input, input_off plus pos plus bi
                proc memory_set_byte from Memory with block_buf, bi, sb
                Set bi to bi plus 1
            End While
            Let pi be this_len
            While pi is less than BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE:
                proc memory_set_byte from Memory with block_buf, pi, 0
                Set pi to pi plus 1
            End While

            Let flags2 be base_flags
            If is_first_block is equal to 1:
                Set flags2 to flags2 bitwise_or BLAKE3_FLAG_CHUNK_START
            End If
            If is_last_block is equal to 1:
                Set flags2 to flags2 bitwise_or BLAKE3_FLAG_CHUNK_END
                Set flags2 to flags2 bitwise_or BLAKE3_FLAG_ROOT
                proc blake3_compress with arena, cv_buf, block_buf, final_chunk_idx, this_len, flags2, root_state_out
            Otherwise:
                proc blake3_compress with arena, cv_buf, block_buf, final_chunk_idx, this_len, flags2, state_scratch
                proc blake3_state_to_cv with state_scratch, cv_buf
            End If

            Set pos to pos plus this_len
            Set is_first_block to 0
        End While
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Multi-chunk case: process the final chunk normally to produce
    Note: a CV, then merge up the stack with ROOT on the final parent.
    proc blake3_compress_chunk with arena, key_cv, input, input_off, remaining, final_chunk_idx, base_flags, chunk_cv

    Let key_cv_ptr be h plus BLAKE3_HASHER_KEY_CV_OFF
    Let base_flags_h be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with h, BLAKE3_HASHER_BASE_FLAGS_OFF

    Note: Now reduce stack with chunk_cv as the rightmost CV, working
    Note: right-to-left. The final merge sets ROOT.
    Let working_cv be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_CV_SIZE
    If working_cv is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let wi be 0
    While wi is less than BLAKE3_CV_SIZE:
        Let cb_w be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with chunk_cv, wi
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with working_cv, wi, cb_w
        Set wi to wi plus 1
    End While

    Let parent_state_scratch be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, 128
    If parent_state_scratch is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let stack_remaining be stack_size_before_final
    While stack_remaining is greater than 0:
        Let stack_top_idx be stack_remaining minus 1
        Let left_off be stack_top_idx multiplied by 32
        Let left_ptr be h plus BLAKE3_HASHER_STACK_OFF plus left_off
        If stack_remaining is equal to 1:
            Note: Final merge: set ROOT.
            Let final_block be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE
            If final_block is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            Let li be 0
            While li is less than 32:
                Let lb_b be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with left_ptr, li
                proc memory_set_byte from Memory with final_block, li, lb_b
                Set li to li plus 1
            End While
            Let ri be 0
            While ri is less than 32:
                Let rb_b be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with working_cv, ri
                proc memory_set_byte from Memory with final_block, ri plus 32, rb_b
                Set ri to ri plus 1
            End While
            Let root_flags be base_flags_h bitwise_or BLAKE3_FLAG_PARENT
            Set root_flags to root_flags bitwise_or BLAKE3_FLAG_ROOT
            proc blake3_compress with arena, key_cv_ptr, final_block, 0, BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE, root_flags, root_state_out
            Return 1
        End If
        proc blake3_parent_cv with arena, key_cv_ptr, left_ptr, working_cv, base_flags_h, parent_state_scratch
        proc blake3_state_to_cv with parent_state_scratch, working_cv
        Set stack_remaining to stack_remaining minus 1
    End While

    Note: Unreachable in well-formed inputs; safety fallback.
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: XOF output: produce arbitrary-length output by re-running the root
Note: compression with an incrementing block counter and ROOT set.
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "blake3_xof_emit" takes arena as Integer, root_state as Integer, output as Integer, output_len as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    The root output is generated by repeatedly recompressing the root
    block (the same block that produced root_state) with an incrementing
    counter and ROOT set. Each call produces 64 bytes; we truncate to
    output_len.

    However, blake3_compress takes a CV, a block, counter, block_len,
    and flags. To emit XOF beyond 64 bytes the caller must hold those
    same inputs. Rather than re-derive them here, this proc takes the
    already-produced *first* 64 bytes as root_state and stops there;
    the higher-level XOF driver below holds the inputs and calls
    blake3_compress for additional blocks with incrementing counter.

    Therefore: this proc just serializes the first up-to-64 bytes of
    root_state into output. The actual incrementing-counter loop lives
    in blake3_hash_xof.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Serialize min(output_len, 64) little-endian bytes from root_state
    into output.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Up to 64 byte stores.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let count be output_len
    If count is greater than 64:
        Set count to 64
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 16:
        Let off_i be i multiplied by 8
        Let w be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with root_state, off_i
        Let base be i multiplied by 4
        Let b0 be w bitwise_and 255
        Let b1 be w divided by 256
        Set b1 to b1 bitwise_and 255
        Let b2 be w divided by 65536
        Set b2 to b2 bitwise_and 255
        Let b3 be w divided by 16777216
        Set b3 to b3 bitwise_and 255
        If base is less than count:
            proc memory_set_byte from Memory with output, base, b0
        End If
        If base plus 1 is less than count:
            proc memory_set_byte from Memory with output, base plus 1, b1
        End If
        If base plus 2 is less than count:
            proc memory_set_byte from Memory with output, base plus 2, b2
        End If
        If base plus 3 is less than count:
            proc memory_set_byte from Memory with output, base plus 3, b3
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Internal: drive the full hash to obtain (output_cv, output_block,
Note: output_counter_base, output_block_len, output_flags_without_ROOT)
Note: for XOF emission.
Note: ============================================================================
Note:
We restructure XOF generation as follows. The "output" of BLAKE3 is
characterized by (CV, block, block_len, flags) that together with a
counter produce 64-byte output blocks. For a single-chunk input the
output is (chunk_cv_before_last, last_block, last_block_len,
base_flags | CHUNK_START_if_first | CHUNK_END). For a multi-chunk
input the output is (key_cv, left_cv||right_cv, 64,
base_flags | PARENT) where left_cv and right_cv are the final two
subtrees.

To support both modes uniformly, blake3_hash_xof:
  - Runs the tree to find the root output's (CV, block, block_len,
    flags_without_ROOT).
  - For each 64-byte slice of output requested, runs blake3_compress
    with counter = slice_index, flags = flags_without_ROOT | ROOT.

We avoid duplicating tree-walking logic by serializing the root output
descriptor into an arena buffer of fixed layout:
  bytes [0..31]:   CV
  bytes [32..95]:  block (64 bytes)
  bytes [96..103]: block_len (qword)
  bytes [104..111]: flags_without_ROOT (qword)
Total: 112 bytes.
:End Note

Constant BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_SIZE as Integer is 112
Constant BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_CV_OFF as Integer is 0
Constant BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_BLOCK_OFF as Integer is 32
Constant BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_BLOCK_LEN_OFF as Integer is 96
Constant BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_FLAGS_OFF as Integer is 104

Process called "blake3_hash_input_to_output_desc" takes arena as Integer, key_cv as Integer, base_flags as Integer, input as Integer, length as Integer, desc as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Drives the BLAKE3 tree and writes the *root output descriptor* into
    desc. The descriptor captures everything needed to compute any 64-byte
    slice of the XOF output: the input CV to the final compression, the
    64-byte block, the block_len, and the flags-without-ROOT. The XOF
    emission loop then re-runs the compression with an incrementing
    counter and ROOT in the flags.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Mirrors blake3_hash_input_to_root_state but, on the final
    compression, instead of running it with ROOT, captures the inputs
    into the descriptor.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Same cost as the non-XOF path; the only difference is the final
    step writes a descriptor instead of running one extra compression.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let h be proc blake3_hasher_init with arena, key_cv, base_flags
    If h is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If length is equal to 0:
        Note: Output descriptor: CV=key_cv, block=zeros, block_len=0,
        Note: flags = base_flags | CHUNK_START | CHUNK_END.
        Let ki3 be 0
        While ki3 is less than 32:
            Let kb3 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with key_cv, ki3
            proc memory_set_byte from Memory with desc, BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_CV_OFF plus ki3, kb3
            Set ki3 to ki3 plus 1
        End While
        Let zi be 0
        While zi is less than BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE:
            proc memory_set_byte from Memory with desc, BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_BLOCK_OFF plus zi, 0
            Set zi to zi plus 1
        End While
        proc memory_set_qword from Memory with desc, BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_BLOCK_LEN_OFF, 0
        Let zflags be base_flags bitwise_or BLAKE3_FLAG_CHUNK_START
        Set zflags to zflags bitwise_or BLAKE3_FLAG_CHUNK_END
        proc memory_set_qword from Memory with desc, BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_FLAGS_OFF, zflags
        Return 1
    End If

    Let input_off be 0
    Let remaining be length
    Let chunk_cv be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_CV_SIZE
    If chunk_cv is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Process complete chunks except final
    While remaining is greater than BLAKE3_CHUNK_SIZE:
        Let chunk_idx be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with h, BLAKE3_HASHER_CHUNK_COUNTER_OFF
        proc blake3_compress_chunk with arena, key_cv, input, input_off, BLAKE3_CHUNK_SIZE, chunk_idx, base_flags, chunk_cv
        Let new_counter be chunk_idx plus 1
        proc memory_set_qword from Memory with h, BLAKE3_HASHER_CHUNK_COUNTER_OFF, new_counter
        proc blake3_push_cv_with_arena with arena, h, chunk_cv
        Set input_off to input_off plus BLAKE3_CHUNK_SIZE
        Set remaining to remaining minus BLAKE3_CHUNK_SIZE
    End While

    Let stack_size_before_final be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with h, BLAKE3_HASHER_STACK_SIZE_OFF
    Let final_chunk_idx be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with h, BLAKE3_HASHER_CHUNK_COUNTER_OFF

    If stack_size_before_final is equal to 0:
        Note: Single chunk total. The root output is the chunk's last
        Note: block. We must replay the chunk processing up to but not
        Note: including the final block.
        Let cv_buf be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_CV_SIZE
        If cv_buf is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let block_buf be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE
        If block_buf is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let state_scratch be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, 128
        If state_scratch is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Init cv = key_cv
        Let ki2 be 0
        While ki2 is less than BLAKE3_CV_SIZE:
            Let kb2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with key_cv, ki2
            proc memory_set_byte from Memory with cv_buf, ki2, kb2
            Set ki2 to ki2 plus 1
        End While

        Let pos be 0
        Let is_first_block be 1
        While pos is less than remaining:
            Let rem_in_chunk be remaining minus pos
            Let this_len be rem_in_chunk
            If this_len is greater than BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE:
                Set this_len to BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE
            End If
            Let is_last_block be 0
            If pos plus this_len is equal to remaining:
                Set is_last_block to 1
            End If

            Let bi be 0
            While bi is less than this_len:
                Let sb be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with input, input_off plus pos plus bi
                proc memory_set_byte from Memory with block_buf, bi, sb
                Set bi to bi plus 1
            End While
            Let pi be this_len
            While pi is less than BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE:
                proc memory_set_byte from Memory with block_buf, pi, 0
                Set pi to pi plus 1
            End While

            Let flags2 be base_flags
            If is_first_block is equal to 1:
                Set flags2 to flags2 bitwise_or BLAKE3_FLAG_CHUNK_START
            End If
            If is_last_block is equal to 1:
                Set flags2 to flags2 bitwise_or BLAKE3_FLAG_CHUNK_END
                Note: Capture descriptor here, do not compress with ROOT yet.
                Let cvi be 0
                While cvi is less than 32:
                    Let cvb be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with cv_buf, cvi
                    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with desc, BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_CV_OFF plus cvi, cvb
                    Set cvi to cvi plus 1
                End While
                Let bbi be 0
                While bbi is less than BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE:
                    Let bbb be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with block_buf, bbi
                    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with desc, BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_BLOCK_OFF plus bbi, bbb
                    Set bbi to bbi plus 1
                End While
                proc memory_set_qword from Memory with desc, BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_BLOCK_LEN_OFF, this_len
                proc memory_set_qword from Memory with desc, BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_FLAGS_OFF, flags2
                Note: We also need the counter for XOF; for a single-chunk
                Note: input the counter is final_chunk_idx (= 0). The XOF
                Note: emitter uses (counter_base + slice_index). For chunk
                Note: output mode we set counter_base = final_chunk_idx.
                Note: This is captured implicitly by storing it as a
                Note: separate field below; here we extend the descriptor
                Note: via an additional convention: callers pass
                Note: final_chunk_idx explicitly to the XOF emitter.
                Note: To avoid an extra parameter, we store the counter as
                Note: a hidden field by widening the descriptor: see
                Note: blake3_xof_emit_from_desc below.
                Note: For chunk-output, counter_base = final_chunk_idx.
                Note: For parent-output, counter_base = 0.
                Return 1
            Otherwise:
                proc blake3_compress with arena, cv_buf, block_buf, final_chunk_idx, this_len, flags2, state_scratch
                proc blake3_state_to_cv with state_scratch, cv_buf
            End If

            Set pos to pos plus this_len
            Set is_first_block to 0
        End While
        Note: Unreachable if length > 0.
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Multi-chunk path. Compute the final chunk's CV (no ROOT, no
    Note: descriptor capture). Then walk the stack right-to-left; the
    Note: final merge becomes the descriptor.
    proc blake3_compress_chunk with arena, key_cv, input, input_off, remaining, final_chunk_idx, base_flags, chunk_cv

    Let key_cv_ptr be h plus BLAKE3_HASHER_KEY_CV_OFF
    Let base_flags_h be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with h, BLAKE3_HASHER_BASE_FLAGS_OFF

    Let working_cv be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_CV_SIZE
    If working_cv is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let wi be 0
    While wi is less than BLAKE3_CV_SIZE:
        Let cb_w be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with chunk_cv, wi
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with working_cv, wi, cb_w
        Set wi to wi plus 1
    End While

    Let parent_state_scratch be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, 128
    If parent_state_scratch is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let stack_remaining be stack_size_before_final
    While stack_remaining is greater than 0:
        Let stack_top_idx be stack_remaining minus 1
        Let left_off be stack_top_idx multiplied by 32
        Let left_ptr be h plus BLAKE3_HASHER_STACK_OFF plus left_off
        If stack_remaining is equal to 1:
            Note: Capture descriptor as a PARENT output (no ROOT).
            Let final_block be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE
            If final_block is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            Let li be 0
            While li is less than 32:
                Let lb_b be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with left_ptr, li
                proc memory_set_byte from Memory with final_block, li, lb_b
                Set li to li plus 1
            End While
            Let ri be 0
            While ri is less than 32:
                Let rb_b be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with working_cv, ri
                proc memory_set_byte from Memory with final_block, ri plus 32, rb_b
                Set ri to ri plus 1
            End While
            Note: Descriptor CV = key_cv
            Let dci be 0
            While dci is less than 32:
                Let dcb be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with key_cv, dci
                proc memory_set_byte from Memory with desc, BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_CV_OFF plus dci, dcb
                Set dci to dci plus 1
            End While
            Let dbi be 0
            While dbi is less than BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE:
                Let dbb be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with final_block, dbi
                proc memory_set_byte from Memory with desc, BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_BLOCK_OFF plus dbi, dbb
                Set dbi to dbi plus 1
            End While
            proc memory_set_qword from Memory with desc, BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_BLOCK_LEN_OFF, BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE
            Let final_flags be base_flags_h bitwise_or BLAKE3_FLAG_PARENT
            proc memory_set_qword from Memory with desc, BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_FLAGS_OFF, final_flags
            Return 1
        End If
        proc blake3_parent_cv with arena, key_cv_ptr, left_ptr, working_cv, base_flags_h, parent_state_scratch
        proc blake3_state_to_cv with parent_state_scratch, working_cv
        Set stack_remaining to stack_remaining minus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Emit XOF output of `output_len` bytes from a captured output descriptor.
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "blake3_xof_emit_from_desc" takes arena as Integer, desc as Integer, counter_base as Integer, output as Integer, output_len as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Per BLAKE3 spec, XOF output is produced by re-running the root
    compression with counter = counter_base + slice_index for slice
    indices 0, 1, 2, ..., each yielding a 64-byte block. ROOT is set
    in every emission. The final slice is truncated to output_len.

    For chunk-style outputs (single-chunk input), counter_base equals
    the chunk's final_chunk_idx (effectively the chunk counter).
    For parent-style outputs (multi-chunk), counter_base is 0.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Reads the descriptor's CV, block, block_len, flags_without_ROOT;
    sets effective_flags = flags_without_ROOT | ROOT; and loops:
      for slice in 0..(ceil(output_len/64)-1):
        run blake3_compress(cv, block, counter_base + slice, block_len,
                            effective_flags, state);
        copy min(64, output_len - slice*64) bytes from the serialized
        state into output[slice*64..].
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One compression per 64 bytes of output. Each compression is ~3-6
    cycles per byte in scalar code.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time per slice.
    @End Security_Scope

    If output_len is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If output_len is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let flags_without_root be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with desc, BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_FLAGS_OFF
    Let effective_flags be flags_without_root bitwise_or BLAKE3_FLAG_ROOT
    Let block_len be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with desc, BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_BLOCK_LEN_OFF

    Let cv_ptr be desc plus BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_CV_OFF
    Let block_ptr be desc plus BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_BLOCK_OFF

    Let state be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, 128
    If state is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let block_out be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE
    If block_out is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let emitted be 0
    Let slice be 0
    While emitted is less than output_len:
        Let counter be counter_base plus slice
        proc blake3_compress with arena, cv_ptr, block_ptr, counter, block_len, effective_flags, state
        proc blake3_state_to_bytes with state, block_out

        Let remaining be output_len minus emitted
        Let to_copy be remaining
        If to_copy is greater than BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE:
            Set to_copy to BLAKE3_BLOCK_SIZE
        End If
        Let ci be 0
        While ci is less than to_copy:
            Let bb be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with block_out, ci
            proc memory_set_byte from Memory with output, emitted plus ci, bb
            Set ci to ci plus 1
        End While

        Set emitted to emitted plus to_copy
        Set slice to slice plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Determine the counter_base for XOF from an input descriptor's flags:
Note:   - PARENT flag set: counter_base = 0
Note:   - PARENT flag clear (chunk-style): counter_base = chunk_counter
Note:     captured separately. To avoid threading that as a parameter, we
Note:     observe that for chunk-style outputs the final_chunk_idx equals
Note:     the total_chunks_minus_1 which is 0 for single-chunk inputs.
Note:     For inputs <= 1024 bytes the counter is always 0.
Note: This invariant lets us compute counter_base from descriptor alone:
Note:   if (flags & PARENT) == 0: counter_base = 0 (single-chunk case)
Note:   if (flags & PARENT) != 0: counter_base = 0 (parent case)
Note: Hence counter_base is always 0 in our top-level entry points.
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "blake3_xof_emit_default" takes arena as Integer, desc as Integer, output as Integer, output_len as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Top-level wrapper that infers counter_base = 0 (true for all single-
    chunk and all parent-style root outputs) and calls
    blake3_xof_emit_from_desc.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Calls blake3_xof_emit_from_desc with counter_base = 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Indirection only.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc blake3_xof_emit_from_desc with arena, desc, 0, output, output_len
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Public API
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "blake3_hash" takes arena as Integer, input as Integer, length as Integer, digest_32 as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Default 32-byte hash. Equivalent to BLAKE3 keyed_hash with key = IV
    bytes and no KEYED_HASH flag, i.e., the canonical hash mode.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Build a 32-byte key_cv buffer initialized from the BLAKE3 IV
       (8 little-endian words).
    2. Call blake3_hash_input_to_output_desc with base_flags = 0.
    3. Emit 32 bytes via blake3_xof_emit_default.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single compression for the 32-byte XOF output plus the tree work
    for the input.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time. No secret-dependent branches. The key_cv built from
    IV is public.
    @End Security_Scope

    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If digest_32 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If length is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If length is greater than 0:
        If input is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If

    Let key_cv be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_CV_SIZE
    If key_cv is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc blake3_default_iv_to_cv with key_cv

    Let desc be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_SIZE
    If desc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let rc be proc blake3_hash_input_to_output_desc with arena, key_cv, 0, input, length, desc
    If rc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc blake3_xof_emit_default with arena, desc, digest_32, BLAKE3_OUT_SIZE
End Process

Process called "blake3_hash_xof" takes arena as Integer, input as Integer, length as Integer, output as Integer, output_len as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    XOF mode: produces output_len bytes of pseudorandom output derived
    from the input.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Identical to blake3_hash except for the final emission step, which
    produces output_len bytes instead of 32.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(output_len / 64) compressions for emission plus O(length) for input
    processing.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time per slice.
    @End Security_Scope

    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If output_len is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If output_len is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    If output is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If length is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If length is greater than 0:
        If input is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If

    Let key_cv be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_CV_SIZE
    If key_cv is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc blake3_default_iv_to_cv with key_cv

    Let desc be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_SIZE
    If desc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let rc be proc blake3_hash_input_to_output_desc with arena, key_cv, 0, input, length, desc
    If rc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc blake3_xof_emit_default with arena, desc, output, output_len
End Process

Process called "blake3_keyed_hash" takes arena as Integer, key_32 as Integer, input as Integer, length as Integer, digest_32 as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    MAC mode. The 32-byte key is used as the initial chaining value at
    every chunk root; the KEYED_HASH flag is set in base_flags.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Sets key_cv = key_32 (32 bytes copied directly; key is already in
    little-endian word form per spec - 8 words of 4 LE bytes each).
    Runs the full tree with base_flags = KEYED_HASH and emits 32 bytes.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Identical to blake3_hash plus a 32-byte key copy.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time. Caller is responsible for keeping key_32 secret. The
    compression function processes the key only as an arithmetic operand
    (it is the initial v[0..7] for every chunk's first compression).
    Side-channel posture matches the rest of the BLAKE3 code.
    @End Security_Scope

    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If key_32 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If digest_32 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If length is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If length is greater than 0:
        If input is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If

    Let key_cv be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_CV_SIZE
    If key_cv is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ki be 0
    While ki is less than BLAKE3_CV_SIZE:
        Let kb be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with key_32, ki
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with key_cv, ki, kb
        Set ki to ki plus 1
    End While

    Let desc be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_SIZE
    If desc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let rc be proc blake3_hash_input_to_output_desc with arena, key_cv, BLAKE3_FLAG_KEYED_HASH, input, length, desc
    If rc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc blake3_xof_emit_default with arena, desc, digest_32, BLAKE3_OUT_SIZE
End Process

Process called "blake3_derive_key" takes arena as Integer, context as Integer, context_len as Integer, key_material as Integer, key_material_len as Integer, output as Integer, output_len as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    KDF mode per BLAKE3 spec section 6. Two passes:
      Pass 1: hash `context` with base_flags = DERIVE_KEY_CONTEXT and
              the default IV as key_cv, producing a 32-byte intermediate
              key.
      Pass 2: hash `key_material` with base_flags = DERIVE_KEY_MATERIAL
              and the intermediate key as key_cv, producing the output.
    The output may be any length; for the canonical 32-byte KDF use
    output_len = 32.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Allocate intermediate_key buffer (32 bytes).
    2. Run pass 1 to derive intermediate_key (always 32 bytes since the
       context is hashed with default-style output of 32 bytes).
    3. Run pass 2: same as keyed_hash but with base_flags =
       DERIVE_KEY_MATERIAL and output_len-byte output.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two full tree hashes. For short contexts (the usual case) pass 1 is
    a single chunk; the cost is dominated by pass 2 which scales with
    key_material_len.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time. The intermediate key is a function of the public
    context string only; it carries no secret information. The
    key_material is the secret input and is processed under the
    intermediate key with side-channel posture identical to keyed_hash.
    @End Security_Scope

    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If output is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If output_len is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If output_len is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    If context_len is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If key_material_len is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If context_len is greater than 0:
        If context is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If
    If key_material_len is greater than 0:
        If key_material is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If

    Note: Pass 1: derive 32-byte intermediate key from context.
    Let iv_cv be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_CV_SIZE
    If iv_cv is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc blake3_default_iv_to_cv with iv_cv

    Let intermediate_key be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_CV_SIZE
    If intermediate_key is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let desc1 be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_SIZE
    If desc1 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rc1 be proc blake3_hash_input_to_output_desc with arena, iv_cv, BLAKE3_FLAG_DERIVE_KEY_CONTEXT, context, context_len, desc1
    If rc1 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rce1 be proc blake3_xof_emit_default with arena, desc1, intermediate_key, BLAKE3_CV_SIZE
    If rce1 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Pass 2: hash key_material under intermediate_key with DERIVE_KEY_MATERIAL.
    Let desc2 be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, BLAKE3_OUTPUT_DESC_SIZE
    If desc2 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rc2 be proc blake3_hash_input_to_output_desc with arena, intermediate_key, BLAKE3_FLAG_DERIVE_KEY_MATERIAL, key_material, key_material_len, desc2
    If rc2 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc blake3_xof_emit_default with arena, desc2, output, output_len
End Process
